THERE ARE CHUNKS OF LAND 
THAT EVEN HAVE STANDING TREES

00:21:21.999 --> 00:21:24.999
THAT HAVE BEEN SEEN FLOATING 
WAY OUT TO SEA IN THE OCEAN.

00:21:24.999 --> 00:21:27.999
AND THOSE COULD EASILY BRING 
SEVERAL SPECIES AT ONCE

00:21:27.999 --> 00:21:29.999
TO A SYSTEM LIKE THIS.

00:21:31.999 --> 00:21:33.250
Alda: 
OF ALL THE IMMIGRANTS HERE

00:21:33.250 --> 00:21:35.999
FEW HAVE ADAPTED 
SO SUCCESSFULLY TO ISLAND LIFE

00:21:35.999 --> 00:21:37.999
AS THE MARINE IGUANAS.

00:21:37.999 --> 00:21:39.999
WHEREVER YOU GO 
ALONG THE SHORELINE

00:21:39.999 --> 00:21:43.999
IGUANAS WILL BE ON DISPLAY, 
SOMETIMES LITERALLY.

00:21:43.999 --> 00:21:45.999
HE'S GREEN ON 
THE TOP AND RED 
ALONG HIS BODY.

00:21:45.999 --> 00:21:46.999
WHAT DOES THAT...

00:21:46.999 --> 00:21:48.999
YEAH, THAT'S 
A BREEDING MALE.

00:21:48.999 --> 00:21:50.417
IT'S THE COLORATION 
THEY GET...

00:21:50.417 --> 00:21:52.417
THAT'S A SIGNAL 
HE'S READY TO BREED?

00:21:52.417 --> 00:21:53.999
THAT HE'S READY.

00:21:53.999 --> 00:21:55.125
THEN HE'LL SET UP 
A TERRITORY

00:21:55.125 --> 00:21:57.999
AND TRY TO ATTRACT 
SOME FEMALES TO IT.

00:21:57.999 --> 00:21:58.999
BUT THAT'S A BIG 
BREEDING MALE.

00:21:58.999 --> 00:21:59.999
BEAUTIFUL, ISN'T IT?

00:21:59.999 --> 00:22:01.999
WHAT DOES HE DO 
TO ATTRACT FEMALES?

00:22:01.999 --> 00:22:02.999
JUST DISPLAY HIS...

00:22:02.999 --> 00:22:04.667
YOU SEE THAT 
HEAD BOBBING.

00:22:04.667 --> 00:22:05.999
THAT'S KIND OF COOL.

00:22:05.999 --> 00:22:06.999
YEAH, RIGHT:

00:22:06.999 --> 00:22:08.999
"LOOK, BABE, I CAN 
DO 20 PUSH-UPS."

00:22:08.999 --> 00:22:09.999
( laughs ): 
YEAH, RIGHT.

00:22:09.999 --> 00:22:10.999
"I'M THE MAN FOR YOU."

00:22:10.999 --> 00:22:12.999
HE'S A BEAUTY, 
THOUGH, ISN'T HE?

00:22:12.999 --> 00:22:13.999
YEAH, HE IS.

00:22:13.999 --> 00:22:15.959
DOESN'T THAT LOOK 
LIKE GODZILLA?

00:22:15.959 --> 00:22:16.999
YEAH.

00:22:16.999 --> 00:22:19.999
Alda: 
CHARLES DARWIN, 
HAD HE EVER HEARD OF GODZILLA

00:22:19.999 --> 00:22:20.999
MIGHT HAVE AGREED:

00:22:20.999 --> 00:22:23.999
"IT IS A HIDEOUS-LOOKING 
CREATURE, STUPID

00:22:23.999 --> 00:22:25.999
"AND SLUGGISH 
IN ITS MOVEMENTS.

00:22:25.999 --> 00:22:27.667
"WHEN IN THE WATER, 
THIS LIZARD SWIMS

00:22:27.667 --> 00:22:28.999
"WITH PERFECT EASE AND QUICKNESS

00:22:28.999 --> 00:22:31.999
"BY A SERPENTINE MOVEMENT 
OF ITS BODY AND FLATTENED TAIL

00:22:31.999 --> 00:22:34.999
"THE LEGS BEING MOTIONLESS 
AND COLLAPSED AT ITS SIDES.

00:22:34.999 --> 00:22:36.999
"I OPENED THE STOMACHS 
OF SEVERAL

00:22:36.999 --> 00:22:40.667
AND FOUND THEM LARGELY DISTENDED 
WITH MINCED SEAWEED."

00:22:41.999 --> 00:22:44.542
DARWIN PUT HIS FINGER 
ON JUST THOSE ADAPTATIONS

00:22:44.542 --> 00:22:46.999
THAT HAVE MADE THE MARINE IGUANA 
FIT SO PERFECTLY

00:22:46.999 --> 00:22:47.999
INTO ITS ISLAND HOME.

00:22:47.999 --> 00:22:49.999
ALL HE WANTS 
IS GREENS, HUH?

00:22:49.999 --> 00:22:50.999
YEAH, UH-HUH.

00:22:50.999 --> 00:22:51.999
I MEAN, VEGETABLES.

00:22:51.999 --> 00:22:54.000
ALL THAT SEA 
LETTUCE, OVA

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:55.999
IS THEIR 
FAVORITE FOOD.

00:22:55.999 --> 00:22:57.999
Alda: 
THE ANCESTORS OF THESE CREATURES

00:22:57.999 --> 00:23:00.417
WERE LIKE ALL THE OTHER LIZARDS 
IN THE WORLD

00:23:00.417 --> 00:23:01.999
SWIMMING ONLY WHEN THEY HAD TO.

00:23:01.999 --> 00:23:04.999
HE MADE IT 
UP THE CLIFF.

00:23:04.999 --> 00:23:08.417
Alda: 
BUT THE GALAPAGOS MARINE 
IGUANAS, AS THEIR NAME IMPLIES

00:23:08.417 --> 00:23:10.999
HAVE TURNED TO THE SEA 
TO SUSTAIN THEM

00:23:10.999 --> 00:23:12.999
EATING AS VIRTUALLY 
THEIR ONLY FOOD

00:23:12.999 --> 00:23:13.999
THE BRIGHT GREEN ALGAE

00:23:13.999 --> 00:23:17.542
THAT GROWS ALL ALONG 
AND BENEATH THE SHORELINE.

00:23:17.542 --> 00:23:19.834
NOT ONLY HAVE THEY BECOME 
EXPERT SWIMMERS

00:23:19.834 --> 00:23:22.999
THEY'VE ALSO DEVELOPED 
THE ABILITY TO DIGEST THE ALGAE

00:23:22.999 --> 00:23:26.417
WITH THE HELP OF A BACTERIUM 
THAT LIVES IN THEIR HIND GUT.

00:23:29.959 --> 00:23:32.959
THIS SPECIALIZATION HAS MADE 
THE MARINE IGUANAS

00:23:32.959 --> 00:23:33.999
THE LORDS OF THE SEASHORE

00:23:33.999 --> 00:23:38.417
BUT IT HAS ALSO LEFT THEM 
EXTREMELY VULNERABLE.

00:23:38.417 --> 00:23:42.999
MARTIN WIKELSKI HAS WITNESSED 
THEIR VULNERABILITY FIRSTHAND.

00:23:42.999 --> 00:23:45.417
WHAT WAS THIS LIKE 
DURING THAT LAST 
GREAT EL NIÑO?

00:23:45.417 --> 00:23:48.999
WELL, IT WAS HORRIBLE.

00:23:48.999 --> 00:23:50.999
THOSE GUYS ARE 
ABOUT TEN PERCENT

00:23:50.999 --> 00:23:52.959
OF ALL THE ANIMALS 
THAT WERE HERE.

00:23:52.959 --> 00:23:53.999
THERE WERE 
TEN TIMES AS MANY?

00:23:53.999 --> 00:23:54.999
TEN TIMES AS MANY.

00:23:54.999 --> 00:23:57.542
AND THEY WERE 
GOING TO FORAGE.

00:23:57.542 --> 00:24:00.999
THEY WERE TRYING TO GET 
THE LAST BITS OF ALGAE

00:24:00.999 --> 00:24:02.999
AND THEN SLOWLY 
WALKING UP THE BEACH.

00:24:02.999 --> 00:24:04.999
AND SOMETIMES THEY DIDN'T 
MAKE IT UP THE BEACH

00:24:04.999 --> 00:24:06.999
SO THEY WOULD JUST SORT 
OF PUT ONE FOOT FORWARD

00:24:06.999 --> 00:24:08.667
AND STILL TRY TO GO UP

00:24:08.667 --> 00:24:11.999
BUT THEN REALLY BAKE 
IN THE SAND, LITERALLY.

00:24:11.999 --> 00:24:13.999
AND THEY JUST ALL DIED 
IN FRONT OF OUR EYES.

00:24:13.999 --> 00:24:17.999
SO WE HAD, I THINK, LIKE 400 
DEAD ANIMALS DURING A FEW WEEKS.

00:24:17.999 --> 00:24:19.250
THAT'S PRETTY AMAZING.

00:24:19.250 --> 00:24:22.999
NOW, WAS THAT BECAUSE ALL THIS 
GREEN WE SEE HERE WAS NOT HERE?

00:24:22.999 --> 00:24:24.999
YEAH, ALL THIS GREEN YOU 
SEE WAS TOTALLY BLACK.

00:24:24.999 --> 00:24:27.999
THERE WAS ABSOLUTELY NOTHING 
GROWING ON THESE ROCKS.

00:24:27.999 --> 00:24:32.417
Alda: 
THE CAUSE OF THE DEVASTATION 
WAS THE 1997-'98 EL NIÑO

00:24:32.417 --> 00:24:34.999
A PLUME OF UNUSUALLY WARM WATER

00:24:34.999 --> 00:24:37.999
THAT WREAKED HAVOC WITH WEATHER 
PATTERNS ALL OVER THE GLOBE.

00:24:37.999 --> 00:24:40.999
ITS IMPACT ON THE GALAPAGOS 
WAS MORE DIRECT

00:24:40.999 --> 00:24:42.999
BATHING THE ISLANDS 
IN WARM WATER

00:24:42.999 --> 00:24:45.999
AND DRIVING OUT THE COLD 
NUTRIENT-RICH CURRENTS

00:24:45.999 --> 00:24:48.999
THAT NORMALLY SUSTAIN 
THE MARINE LIFE HERE.

00:24:48.999 --> 00:24:53.999
EVERYTHING ON AND 
AROUND THE ISLANDS THAT 
LIVES OFF THE SEA SUFFERED

00:24:53.999 --> 00:24:55.999
BUT THE MARINE IGUANAS

00:24:55.999 --> 00:24:58.667
WHOSE SOLE SOURCE OF FOOD 
WITHERED AWAY

00:24:58.667 --> 00:24:59.999
SUFFERED THE MOST.

00:24:59.999 --> 00:25:02.999
BUT IT TURNS OUT 
THAT EVEN DURING GOOD YEARS

00:25:02.999 --> 00:25:06.000
THE MARINE IGUANAS HERE 
ON THE ISLAND OF GENOVESA

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.542
HAVE TO STRUGGLE 
TO MAKE A LIVING.

00:25:08.542 --> 00:25:09.999
Alda: 
WHY DO WE SEE

00:25:09.999 --> 00:25:10.999
SO MANY SMALLISH 
IGUANAS HERE?

00:25:10.999 --> 00:25:11.999
RIGHT.

00:25:11.999 --> 00:25:14.000
THIS ISLAND GETS 
LEAST OF THE NUTRIENTS.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:15.999
AND THAT MEANS 
THAT THIS ALGAE...

00:25:15.999 --> 00:25:18.542
YOU PROBABLY SAW IGUANAS 
FORAGING ALREADY.

00:25:18.542 --> 00:25:19.999
YES.

00:25:19.999 --> 00:25:22.000
THEY SOMETIMES HAVE 
THESE HUGE ALGAE PASTURES

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.999
AND THEY JUST GET 
A MOUTHFUL OF ALGAE EVERY BITE.

00:25:24.999 --> 00:25:27.999
BUT HERE THEY ONLY HAVE 
A TINY LITTLE CARPET OF ALGAE

00:25:27.999 --> 00:25:29.999
AND THEY CONSTANTLY 
HAVE TO SCRAPE IT OFF.

00:25:29.999 --> 00:25:31.667
SO THAT HAS SELECTED 
OUT THE BIG ONES.

00:25:31.667 --> 00:25:32.959
RIGHT, ABSOLUTELY.

00:25:32.959 --> 00:25:34.417
THE BIG ONES 
THAT MIGHT BE BORN HERE

00:25:34.417 --> 00:25:36.999
JUST AREN'T GOING TO GET 
ENOUGH NUTRIENTS.

00:25:36.999 --> 00:25:37.999
YEAH, ABSOLUTELY.

00:25:37.999 --> 00:25:38.999
THAT'S INTERESTING.

00:25:38.999 --> 00:25:39.999
SO THERE THEY ARE.

00:25:39.999 --> 00:25:40.999
THAT'S THE PRODUCT

00:25:40.999 --> 00:25:42.834
OF NATURAL SELECTION 
RIGHT THERE.

00:25:42.834 --> 00:25:44.999
Alda: 
BUT EVEN AMONG THESE 
SMALLER-THAN-AVERAGE ANIMALS

00:25:44.999 --> 00:25:46.999
SOME OF THE MALES ARE 
CLEARLY LARGER.

00:25:46.999 --> 00:25:50.999
THIS BIG GUY 
HAS WALKED THROUGH 
THE ENTIRE COLLECTION

00:25:50.999 --> 00:25:52.999
DOING THAT 
NODDING THING

00:25:52.999 --> 00:25:55.999
WHICH IS TO ANNOUNCE 
HIS TERRITORY, RIGHT?

00:25:55.999 --> 00:25:56.999
RIGHT.

00:25:56.999 --> 00:25:59.667
BUT IS HE THE ONLY ONE 
IN THIS WHOLE BATCH

00:25:59.667 --> 00:26:00.999
THAT'S DOMINANT 
LIKE THAT?

00:26:00.999 --> 00:26:01.999
HE'S THE HOT SHOT.

00:26:01.999 --> 00:26:03.834
HE'S DEFINITELY 
THE PRIZE MALE

00:26:03.834 --> 00:26:05.999
BECAUSE YOU SEE 
ALL THESE FEMALES 
AROUND HERE?

00:26:05.999 --> 00:26:07.999
THEY ALL LIKE 
TO HANG OUT WITH HIM.

00:26:07.999 --> 00:26:10.667
SO THE FEMALES ARE 
THE ONES THAT CHOOSE 
IN THIS SYSTEM

00:26:10.667 --> 00:26:12.834
AND THE MALES JUST 
TRY TO DO THEIR BEST.

00:26:12.834 --> 00:26:15.999
THE FEMALES ARE ATTRACTED 
TO THIS BIG HANDSOME GUY--

00:26:15.999 --> 00:26:17.999
THIS UGLY THING HERE.

00:26:17.999 --> 00:26:18.999
WAIT, HE'S NOT UGLY.

00:26:18.999 --> 00:26:20.999
I KNOW YOU COME 
HERE EVERY DAY

00:26:20.999 --> 00:26:23.999
AND YOU KIND OF LIKE 
THE WAY THEY LOOK NOW

00:26:23.999 --> 00:26:26.959
BUT I'M TELLING YOU, 
I JUST GOT HERE...

00:26:26.959 --> 00:26:27.999
YOU SHOULD BE 
HERE 30 DAYS

00:26:27.999 --> 00:26:28.999
AND YOU'LL LIKE THEM.

00:26:28.999 --> 00:26:29.999
YEAH, RIGHT, 
OKAY, OKAY.

00:26:29.999 --> 00:26:32.834
Alda: 
YES, MARTIN ACTUALLY DOES SPEND

00:26:32.834 --> 00:26:36.542
THE ENTIRE 30 DAYS THE IGUANAS 
HERE ARE DECIDING ON MATES

00:26:36.542 --> 00:26:39.959
WATCHING TO SEE 
WHICH MALES THE FEMALES PICK.

00:26:39.959 --> 00:26:42.999
IT'S AN IMPORTANT DECISION.

00:26:42.999 --> 00:26:44.999
EACH OF THOSE FEMALES 
ONLY HAS ONE EGG.

00:26:44.999 --> 00:26:45.999
OH, REALLY?

00:26:45.999 --> 00:26:47.417
IT'S ABSOLUTELY AMAZING.

00:26:47.417 --> 00:26:49.999
THEY HAVE ABOUT 25% 
OF THEIR BODY MASS 
IN ONE EGG.

00:26:49.999 --> 00:26:51.667
SO IT REALLY COUNTS 
WHO THEY CHOOSE.

00:26:51.667 --> 00:26:52.999
ABSOLUTELY.

00:26:52.999 --> 00:26:55.250
Alda: 
MARTIN IS TRYING TO UNDERSTAND

00:26:55.250 --> 00:26:57.999
WHY-- IF THE BIG GUYS 
ARE SO POPULAR--

00:26:57.999 --> 00:27:01.999
THE GROUP HERE ALSO CONTAINS 
A NUMBER OF MUCH SMALLER MALES

00:27:01.999 --> 00:27:05.999
WHO, INSTEAD OF SHOWING OFF, 
KEEP A DELIBERATELY LOW PROFILE.

00:27:05.999 --> 00:27:06.999
SEE THAT GUY?

00:27:06.999 --> 00:27:09.125
HE WAS SORT OF SNEAKING 
UP ON THE FEMALE

00:27:09.125 --> 00:27:10.999
TRYING TO GET HER.

00:27:10.999 --> 00:27:12.999
THAT'S ONE OF THE SMALL 
SNEAKER MALES

00:27:12.999 --> 00:27:14.999
THAT HANG OUT 
IN THE TERRITORIES

00:27:14.999 --> 00:27:17.999
AND THEY TRY TO SORT OF 
SNEAK UP ON THE FEMALES.

00:27:17.999 --> 00:27:19.667
THEY'RE ABOUT 
THE FEMALES' SIZE

00:27:19.667 --> 00:27:21.999
SO THE MALE CAN'T TELL 
THEM FROM FEMALES.

00:27:21.999 --> 00:27:24.250
SO THEY JUST TRY 
TO SNEAK UP ON FEMALES

00:27:24.250 --> 00:27:26.999
AND TRY TO MATE WITH 
THEM, IF THEY CAN.

00:27:26.999 --> 00:27:28.999
SO IN A WAY 
HE GETS AN ADVANTAGE.

00:27:28.999 --> 00:27:31.417
HE HAS A CHANCE 
TO SNEAK UP

00:27:31.417 --> 00:27:33.999
BECAUSE HE'S 
A FEMALE IMPERSONATOR

00:27:33.999 --> 00:27:35.999
RIGHT UP UNTIL 
THE LAST MOMENT.

00:27:35.999 --> 00:27:37.999
YEP, YEP.

00:27:37.999 --> 00:27:41.999
Alda: 
THERE MUST BE SOME REASON 
THE FEMALES ACCEPT THE SNEAKERS

00:27:41.999 --> 00:27:45.417
OR NATURAL SELECTION WOULD HAVE 
LONG SINCE HAVE ELIMINATED THEM.

00:27:45.417 --> 00:27:48.999
MARTIN'S HYPOTHESIS IS THAT 
KEEPING SMALLNESS GENES AROUND

00:27:48.999 --> 00:27:52.999
PROVIDES THE FEMALES 
WITH A SORT OF INSURANCE POLICY

00:27:52.999 --> 00:27:54.999
AGAINST THOSE 
BRUTAL EL NIÑO YEARS

00:27:54.999 --> 00:27:56.999
WHEN BEING BIG CAN BE FATAL.

00:27:56.999 --> 00:27:57.999
AND THAT SEEMS TO BE

00:27:57.999 --> 00:27:59.999
SORT OF A LONG-TERM STRATEGY

00:27:59.999 --> 00:28:02.999
THAT THEY CAN'T REALLY KNOW 
WHEN THE NEXT EL NIÑO HITS

00:28:02.999 --> 00:28:05.999
SO SOMETIMES THEY MIGHT 
JUST CHOOSE A SMALL GUY

00:28:05.999 --> 00:28:08.999
AS A MATING PARTNER 
TO HAVE SOME SMALLER OFFSPRING

00:28:08.999 --> 00:28:11.999
AND AT SOME OTHER TIMES 
THEY MIGHT CHOOSE A BIGGER ONE.

00:28:11.999 --> 00:28:12.999
ONE YEAR 
YOU TRY IT BIG

00:28:12.999 --> 00:28:14.417
NEXT YEAR 
YOU TRY IT SMALL

00:28:14.417 --> 00:28:16.999
AND YOU PROTECT YOURSELF 
ALL THE WAY AROUND.

00:28:16.999 --> 00:28:17.999
HE'S NOT GOING 
TO MIND THIS

00:28:17.999 --> 00:28:18.999
COMING IN HIS FACE?

00:28:18.999 --> 00:28:20.000
WELL...

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:21.999
DO IT SLOWLY AND...

00:28:21.999 --> 00:28:24.999
Alda: 
IN THE COURSE OF TESTING 
HIS INSURANCE IDEA

00:28:24.999 --> 00:28:28.999
MARTIN HAS CAUGHT THOUSANDS OF 
MARINE IGUANAS HERE ON GENOVESA.

00:28:28.999 --> 00:28:30.999
THE LEAST I CAN DO 
IS LEND A HAND WITH ONE.

00:28:32.999 --> 00:28:34.999
( Wikelski chuckles )

00:28:34.999 --> 00:28:36.999
NOW HE PROBABLY 
IS ON TO THIS.

00:28:36.999 --> 00:28:38.999
HE'S NOT GOING 
TO LIKE THIS AT ALL.

00:28:40.999 --> 00:28:41.999
WOW, THAT'S A GOOD ONE.

00:28:45.999 --> 00:28:46.999
EXCELLENT.

00:28:47.999 --> 00:28:49.999
I HAVE GOOD BEGINNER'S LUCK.

00:28:49.999 --> 00:28:51.000
( chuckling )

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:54.999
Alda: 
THIS IGUANA WAS FIRST 
CAUGHT AND MARKED BY MARTIN

00:28:54.999 --> 00:28:55.999
WHEN IT WAS A HATCHLING.

00:28:55.999 --> 00:28:59.999
12 YEARS LATER, IT'S ONE 
OF THE KINGS AROUND HERE.

00:28:59.999 --> 00:29:02.667
BUT IF ANOTHER EL NIÑO COMES 
AND THIS GUY'S TOO BIG

00:29:02.667 --> 00:29:05.999
THEN WE BASICALLY FIND 
HIS BODY ON THE BEACH SOMEDAY.

00:29:05.999 --> 00:29:06.999
THAT'S THE FIRST ONE 
FOR THE SEASON.

00:29:06.999 --> 00:29:08.999
JUST GIVE HIM AN "A."

00:29:08.999 --> 00:29:11.999
Alda: 
THE PAINT WILL MAKE IT EASIER 
TO KEEP AN EYE ON HIM.

00:29:11.999 --> 00:29:14.999
IS IT POSSIBLE 
THAT THIS WILL 
TURN OUT TO BE

00:29:14.999 --> 00:29:15.999
SOME CUE TO THE FEMALES

00:29:15.999 --> 00:29:17.999
THAT THIS GUY SHOULD 
BE AVOIDED AT ALL COSTS?

00:29:17.999 --> 00:29:18.999
THAT'S 
A GOOD POINT.

00:29:18.999 --> 00:29:20.000
DO THEY TAKE 
ANY VISUAL CUES?

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.667
MANY PEOPLE AT 
CONFERENCES ASK ME.

00:29:22.667 --> 00:29:23.999
OH, YEAH?

00:29:23.999 --> 00:29:26.834
WE DID TEST IT 
BECAUSE IN ANOLES, 
IN OTHER LIZARDS

00:29:26.834 --> 00:29:27.999
IT WOULD MAKE 
A BIG DIFFERENCE

00:29:27.999 --> 00:29:29.999
BUT IN THOSE GUYS 
IT DOESN'T.

00:29:29.999 --> 00:29:31.999
SO THE FEMALES DON'T 
GO FOR COLORATION.

00:29:31.999 --> 00:29:34.999
THEY DON'T CARE 
ABOUT THE MARKINGS 
WE PUT ON THEM

00:29:34.999 --> 00:29:37.250
AND THEY PROBABLY 
ONLY GO FOR THE SIZE

00:29:37.250 --> 00:29:38.999
AND FOR THE BEHAVIOR.

00:29:38.999 --> 00:29:39.999
YEAH, BUT THIS GUY

00:29:39.999 --> 00:29:41.999
IS NOW CLEARLY 
A MOVIE STAR.

00:29:41.999 --> 00:29:43.999
I MEAN, 
THEY'RE GOING TO...

00:29:43.999 --> 00:29:45.999
AREN'T THEY GOING 
TO NOTICE THAT?

00:29:45.999 --> 00:29:47.667
THAT IS TRUE.

00:29:47.667 --> 00:29:49.667
SO THAT'S IT 
FOR THIS GUY.

00:29:49.667 --> 00:29:50.999
WE CAN LET HIM GO.

00:29:50.999 --> 00:29:52.999
OKAY.

00:29:52.999 --> 00:29:55.999
Alda: 
MARTIN WIKELSKI ISN'T 
THE FIRST SCIENTIST

00:29:55.999 --> 00:29:59.000
TO CATCH AND RELEASE MARINE 
IGUANAS HERE IN THE GALAPAGOS:

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:02.667
"I THREW ONE SEVERAL TIMES 
AS FAR AS I COULD

00:30:02.667 --> 00:30:05.999
"INTO A DEEP POOL LEFT 
BY THE RETIRING TIDE;

00:30:05.999 --> 00:30:07.999
"BUT IT INVARIABLY RETURNED 
IN A DIRECT LINE

00:30:07.999 --> 00:30:09.999
"TO THE SPOT WHERE I STOOD.

00:30:09.999 --> 00:30:12.125
"PERHAPS THIS SINGULAR PIECE 
OF APPARENT STUPIDITY

00:30:12.125 --> 00:30:14.667
"MAY BE ACCOUNTED FOR 
BY THE CIRCUMSTANCE

00:30:14.667 --> 00:30:16.999
"THAT THIS REPTILE HAS 
NO ENEMY WHATEVER ON THE SHORE

00:30:16.999 --> 00:30:20.250
"WHEREAS AT SEA 
IT MUST OFTEN FALL A PREY

00:30:20.250 --> 00:30:21.999
"TO THE NUMEROUS SHARKS.

00:30:21.999 --> 00:30:25.999
"HENCE, PROBABLY, URGED BY 
A FIXED AND HEREDITARY INSTINCT

00:30:25.999 --> 00:30:28.125
"THAT THE SHORE IS 
ITS PLACE OF SAFETY

00:30:28.125 --> 00:30:31.999
WHATEVER THE EMERGENCY MAY BE, 
IT THERE TAKES REFUGE."

00:30:33.999 --> 00:30:35.999
Alda: 
LATE ONE AFTERNOON

00:30:35.999 --> 00:30:37.999
LYNN AND I FOUND OURSELVES 
STEPPING CAREFULLY

00:30:37.999 --> 00:30:40.417
TO AVOID MARINE IGUANAS 
LOUNGING BEFORE BEDTIME

00:30:40.417 --> 00:30:43.999
ALL OVER THE WATERFRONT 
OF THE ISLAND OF FERNANDINA.

00:30:43.999 --> 00:30:45.999
OOPS, ALMOST STEPPED 
ON ITS TAIL.

00:30:45.999 --> 00:30:48.999
Alda: 
I REMEMBER MY SURPRISED 
AND DELIGHTED REACTION

00:30:48.999 --> 00:30:52.417
TO THE FIRST MARINE IGUANA 
I SAW ONLY A FEW DAYS AGO.

00:30:52.417 --> 00:30:55.999
BUT ALREADY THEY'VE BECOME 
SIMPLY PART OF THE PLACE.

00:30:57.999 --> 00:31:00.999
BUT JUST WATCH THEM FOR A WHILE.

00:31:01.999 --> 00:31:03.999
WHAT AN EXTRAORDINARY STORY 
THEY TELL.

00:31:03.999 --> 00:31:08.542
FOR HUNDREDS OF THOUSANDS, 
PERHAPS MILLIONS OF YEARS

00:31:08.542 --> 00:31:10.999
THEY'VE LIVED AND DIED HERE

00:31:10.999 --> 00:31:13.000
SLOWLY SCULPTED 
BY THAT LIVING AND DYING

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.999
FROM THE LAND CREATURES 
THEY ONCE WERE

00:31:15.999 --> 00:31:18.999
INTO THE IMPERIOUS MASTERS 
OF THEIR NEW MARINE ENVIRONMENT.

00:31:23.999 --> 00:31:25.999
IT'S A STORY THAT, 
FOR ONE GIDDY MOMENT

00:31:25.999 --> 00:31:28.999
IT SEEMS TO ME 
THEY DESERVE TO HEAR.

00:31:28.999 --> 00:31:29.999
NO, I'M SERIOUS.

00:31:29.999 --> 00:31:32.667
THERE'S THIS GUY CHARLES DARWIN 
WHO SAYS IT'S SO.

00:31:32.667 --> 00:31:33.999
LOOK, YOU HAVE TO BELIEVE ME.

00:31:33.999 --> 00:31:37.542
YOU ALL DESCENDED FROM 
SOME LIZARD A LONG TIME AGO.

00:31:37.542 --> 00:31:39.999
WHO... COULD I SEE 
A SHOW OF CLAWS?

00:31:39.999 --> 00:31:40.999
WHO BELIEVES THAT?

00:31:58.250 --> 00:32:00.959
Alda: 
I SHOULD HAVE KNOWN 
FROM MY FIRST ENCOUNTER

00:32:00.959 --> 00:32:01.999
WITH A BIRD CALLED 
THE MASKED BOOBY

00:32:01.999 --> 00:32:03.999
THAT THIS IS A CREATURE 
WITH A STRANGE SENSE

00:32:03.999 --> 00:32:04.999
OF RIGHT AND WRONG.

00:32:04.999 --> 00:32:06.417
WHOOP.

00:32:07.999 --> 00:32:08.999
HOLD TIGHT... 
OKAY, OKAY!

00:32:08.999 --> 00:32:09.999
( chuckling )

00:32:09.999 --> 00:32:10.999
WE GOT 
A LITTLE CLOSE

00:32:10.999 --> 00:32:12.999
TO THE GUANO 
RING THERE.

00:32:12.999 --> 00:32:14.999
Alda: 
MY SECOND ENCOUNTER CAME

00:32:14.999 --> 00:32:16.999
IN THE COMPANY 
OF DAVE ANDERSON.

00:32:16.999 --> 00:32:17.999
( squawks )

00:32:17.999 --> 00:32:19.542
ALL RIGHT, ALAN.

00:32:19.542 --> 00:32:21.999
HERE WE'VE GOT 
A NESTLING MASKED BOOBY

00:32:21.999 --> 00:32:23.959
WITH ITS PARENT

00:32:23.959 --> 00:32:24.999
WHO HAS CONVENIENTLY 
STEPPED ASIDE

00:32:24.999 --> 00:32:27.999
SO THAT WE CAN PUT 
A BAND ON ITS CHICK.

00:32:27.999 --> 00:32:30.999
Alda: 
DAVE HAS BEEN STUDYING MASKED 
BOOBIES FOR HALF HIS LIFE

00:32:30.999 --> 00:32:33.999
TRYING TO UNDERSTAND 
A SINGULARLY GRUESOME FACT...

00:32:33.999 --> 00:32:35.999
GENTLY GRAB 
THE BIRD.

00:32:35.999 --> 00:32:39.250
Alda: 
THAT THIS YOUNG BOOBY, ALL 
FLUFFY AND APPARENTLY INNOCENT

00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:40.999
MAY WELL HAVE 
COMMITTED MURDER.

00:32:40.999 --> 00:32:46.999
THIS IS MAYBE 
A 35-, 40-DAY-OLD 
MASKED BOOBY CHICK

00:32:46.999 --> 00:32:48.999
AND IT CAN GIVE 
YOU A GOOD NIP.

00:32:48.999 --> 00:32:50.999
SO IF YOU WOULD LIKE 
TO HOLD THIS BIRD...

00:32:50.999 --> 00:32:51.999
IT COULD GIVE YOU 
A GOOD NIP

00:32:51.999 --> 00:32:53.250
SO IF I WOULD 
LIKE TO HOLD IT?

00:32:53.250 --> 00:32:54.999
IS THAT, LIKE, 
AN ACTUAL SENTENCE?

00:32:54.999 --> 00:32:55.999
YEAH, NOW, 
DON'T SQUEEZE IT.

00:32:55.999 --> 00:32:58.999
JUST GET UP 
AROUND THE HEAD SO...

00:32:58.999 --> 00:33:01.999
Alda: 
NOT ONLY IS THIS BABY BOOBY 
A NATURAL-BORN KILLER;

00:33:01.999 --> 00:33:04.999
THE CREATURE IT MAY HAVE KILLED 
WAS ITS OWN SIBLING.

00:33:04.999 --> 00:33:06.999
WE'RE GOING TO GIVE 
THIS BIRD A NAME.

00:33:06.999 --> 00:33:08.999
PROBABLY ALREADY 
HAS A NAME

00:33:08.999 --> 00:33:12.250
BUT THIS IS WHAT I'M 
GOING TO CALL IT: 95289.

00:33:12.250 --> 00:33:15.542
Alda: 
DAVE ANDERSON WANTS TO KNOW 
WHY THE MURDER OCCURRED.

00:33:15.542 --> 00:33:16.999
EVEN MORE, HE WANTS TO KNOW

00:33:16.999 --> 00:33:19.125
WHY THE PARENTS DID 
NOTHING TO STOP IT.

00:33:19.125 --> 00:33:22.999
AND WE'LL PUT THIS 
LITTLE CHICK BACK IN HIS HOME.

00:33:22.999 --> 00:33:23.999
LITTLE CHICK NEEDS TO CALM DOWN.

00:33:23.999 --> 00:33:25.999
THERE.

00:33:27.999 --> 00:33:29.999
Alda: 
TO ANSWER THESE QUESTIONS

00:33:29.999 --> 00:33:31.999
ANDERSON HAS BEEN COMING HERE 
TO THE ISLAND OF ESPAÑOLA

00:33:31.999 --> 00:33:34.999
FOR 20 YEARS.

00:33:34.999 --> 00:33:37.125
MASKED BOOBIES BREED IN COLONIES

00:33:37.125 --> 00:33:39.999
AND THINGS START OFF 
ROMANTICALLY ENOUGH.

00:33:39.999 --> 00:33:41.999
SOME OF THESE BIRDS 
DON'T HAVE A MATE.

00:33:41.999 --> 00:33:43.999
AND SO WHEN THEY'RE 
TRYING TO FIND ONE

00:33:43.999 --> 00:33:45.999
THEY CHECK OUT 
DIFFERENT POSSIBILITIES

00:33:45.999 --> 00:33:46.999
AND THEY GET TOGETHER

00:33:46.999 --> 00:33:48.999
AND THEY MAYBE HAVE 
A DATE FOR AN AFTERNOON

00:33:48.999 --> 00:33:50.999
WHERE THEY GIVE EACH 
OTHER LITTLE GIFTS--

00:33:50.999 --> 00:33:53.959
TWIGS AND STUFF LIKE THAT-- 
AND IF THEY'RE NOT COMPATIBLE

00:33:53.959 --> 00:33:54.999
THEY'LL KNOW PRETTY QUICKLY

00:33:54.999 --> 00:33:57.542
AND IF THEY ARE COMPATIBLE, 
MAYBE THEY'LL CONTINUE.

00:33:57.542 --> 00:34:00.999
IT'S A LOT LIKE A SPECIES 
WE KNOW PRETTY WELL.

00:34:00.999 --> 00:34:04.999
MOST BIRDS IN OTHER SPECIES MAKE 
A NEST AND MASKED BOOBIES DON'T.

00:34:04.999 --> 00:34:08.999
BUT THE BUILDING OF A NEST 
AND ACCUMULATION OF MATERIAL

00:34:08.999 --> 00:34:10.999
AND SHOWING WHAT 
A GREAT TWIG YOU'VE GOT

00:34:10.999 --> 00:34:11.999
IS STILL PART OF THE RITUAL.

00:34:11.999 --> 00:34:13.999
SO IT'S ANOTHER WAY 
OF SAYING, YOU KNOW

00:34:13.999 --> 00:34:15.250
"I'M IN A FAMILY WAY.

00:34:15.250 --> 00:34:16.999
"ARE YOU?

00:34:16.999 --> 00:34:17.999
"DO YOU LIKE THIS TWIG?

00:34:17.999 --> 00:34:19.999
"MAYBE IF WE LIKE 
THE SAME KIND OF TWIG

00:34:19.999 --> 00:34:21.250
WE MIGHT BE ABLE 
TO GET TOGETHER."

00:34:21.250 --> 00:34:22.999
( booby whistles )

00:34:24.999 --> 00:34:27.959
Alda: 
BUT ONCE THE WEDDING BELLS 
HAVE RUNG

00:34:27.959 --> 00:34:31.667
THE HARSH REALITY 
OF MASKED BOOBY LIFE BEGINS.

00:34:31.667 --> 00:34:35.250
Anderson: 
THIS PARENT HAS 
TWO CHICKS UNDER IT.

00:34:35.250 --> 00:34:37.999
ONE OF THEM HATCHED 
ABOUT SEVEN DAYS AGO

00:34:37.999 --> 00:34:40.959
AND THE OTHER ONE HATCHED 
OUT OF THIS EGGSHELL

00:34:40.959 --> 00:34:41.999
ABOUT TWO DAYS AGO.

00:34:41.999 --> 00:34:43.999
WHEN THE SECOND CHICK HATCHED

00:34:43.999 --> 00:34:45.999
IT WAS A SMALLER SIZE 
AND LESS CAPABLE

00:34:45.999 --> 00:34:47.000
AND THE FIRST CHICK

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:50.999
IS GOING TO PUSH THIS HELPLESS 
SECOND CHICK OUT OF THE NEST

00:34:50.999 --> 00:34:52.999
IF IT BEHAVES LIKE 
NORMAL MASKED BOOBY CHICKS.

00:34:52.999 --> 00:34:54.999
Alda: 
FOR THE FIRST FEW DAYS

00:34:54.999 --> 00:34:57.999
THE CHICKS AMICABLY 
SHARE THEIR NEST.

00:34:57.999 --> 00:35:00.999
BUT ON DAY FIVE, 
THINGS TURN NASTY.

00:35:02.999 --> 00:35:04.999
( chick squeals )

00:35:14.999 --> 00:35:16.999
( younger chick squeaks feebly )

00:35:16.999 --> 00:35:18.999
( parent bird squawks )

00:35:32.999 --> 00:35:36.999
Alda: 
THE MAIN THING THE PARENT 
IS PROVIDING FOR THE CHICKS

00:35:36.999 --> 00:35:39.125
IS SHELTER FROM THE GLARING SUN.

00:35:39.125 --> 00:35:41.999
THE OLDER CHICK IS TRYING 
TO PUSH THE YOUNGER

00:35:41.999 --> 00:35:45.999
OUT FROM THE SHADE, 
TO A SLOW BUT CERTAIN DEATH.

00:35:45.999 --> 00:35:46.999
THROUGHOUT THE STRUGGLE

00:35:46.999 --> 00:35:50.417
THE PARENT REMAINS ALOOF 
AND APPARENTLY INDIFFERENT.

00:35:50.417 --> 00:35:54.999
Anderson: 
THE PARENT IS NOT GOING TO DO 
ANYTHING ABOUT THIS SIBLICIDE--

00:35:54.999 --> 00:35:57.999
WE CALL IT SIBLICIDE, 
THE KILLING OF A SIBLING.

00:35:57.999 --> 00:35:59.999
IF IT'S LIKE MOST 
MASKED BOOBY PARENTS

00:35:59.999 --> 00:36:02.999
IT WILL SIMPLY WATCH OR LOOK 
AROUND OR DO SOMETHING ELSE

00:36:02.999 --> 00:36:05.834
BUT IT WILL NOT HELP 
THIS POOR OFFSPRING

00:36:05.834 --> 00:36:07.999
THAT'S BEING KILLED 
BY ITS OWN SIBLING.

00:36:10.999 --> 00:36:12.999
THE FIRST TIME I SAW THIS HAPPEN

00:36:12.999 --> 00:36:16.999
I COULDN'T BELIEVE WHAT 
BAD LUCK THE "B" CHICK HAD.

00:36:16.999 --> 00:36:18.250
ITS CLOSEST RELATIVE 
IN THE WORLD

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:20.959
IS THROWING IT OUT OF THE NEST

00:36:20.959 --> 00:36:23.834
TO DIE ON THE HOT GROUND 
OF SUNSTROKE.

00:36:23.834 --> 00:36:25.999
UM... IT'S SORT OF 
A MISERABLE THING TO SEE.

00:36:25.999 --> 00:36:26.999
I'VE SEEN IT ENOUGH TIMES NOW

00:36:26.999 --> 00:36:29.999
THAT I ACCEPT THAT THAT'S 
THE NORMAL WAY OF BOOBY LIFE

00:36:29.999 --> 00:36:32.000
BUT IT IS KIND OF SHOCKING 
THE FIRST TIME YOU SEE IT.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:35.999
Alda: 
SHOCKING, AND IN 
DARWINIAN TERMS BAFFLING

00:36:35.999 --> 00:36:37.999
AT LEAST AT FIRST SIGHT.

00:36:37.999 --> 00:36:42.999
AFTER ALL, THAT'S THE PARENT'S 
OWN GENES LYING THERE DYING.

00:36:42.999 --> 00:36:45.999
Alda: 
I DON'T UNDERSTAND 
THE ECONOMICS OF THIS.

00:36:45.999 --> 00:36:47.999
IF SHE'S GOING TO LAY TWO EGGS

00:36:47.999 --> 00:36:49.000
AND EVERYBODY KNOWS

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.999
THAT THE FIRST ONE IS GOING 
TO KILL THE SECOND ONE

00:36:51.999 --> 00:36:54.999
WHY EXPEND ALL THAT ENERGY 
TO LAY A SECOND EGG?

00:36:54.999 --> 00:36:56.667
IT SEEMS 
LIKE A WASTE.

00:36:56.667 --> 00:36:57.999
YEAH.

00:36:57.999 --> 00:36:59.125
IN TERMS OF NATURAL SELECTION

00:36:59.125 --> 00:37:02.999
SELECTION IS GOING 
TO MAXIMIZE THE EXCESS BENEFITS

00:37:02.999 --> 00:37:05.417
OVER THE COST.

00:37:05.417 --> 00:37:07.999
SO CERTAINLY THE BENEFIT 
HAS TO EXCEED THE COST.

00:37:07.999 --> 00:37:10.999
IN THIS CASE, THERE'S A BENEFIT 
TO LAYING THE SECOND EGG

00:37:10.999 --> 00:37:12.125
EVEN IF YOU ONLY WANT ONE CHICK

00:37:12.125 --> 00:37:14.542
BECAUSE THEY HAVE 
LOUSY HATCHING SUCCESS.

00:37:14.542 --> 00:37:16.417
THEY ONLY HATCH 
ABOUT 60% OF THEIR EGGS

00:37:16.417 --> 00:37:18.999
EVEN IF YOU ELIMINATE 
ACCIDENTS AND STUFF.

00:37:18.999 --> 00:37:21.999
SOMETHING ABOUT FERTILITY 
OR EMBRYO DEVELOPMENT

00:37:21.999 --> 00:37:23.999
CAUSES 40% OF THEM TO DIE.

00:37:23.999 --> 00:37:25.125
SO IF YOU'RE GOING 
TO GET ONE CHICK--

00:37:25.125 --> 00:37:26.999
YOU GOT TO HAVE ONE CHICK--

00:37:26.999 --> 00:37:28.999
YOU'RE PREPARED TO PAY 
THE PRICE OF A SECOND EGG

00:37:28.999 --> 00:37:32.250
EVEN THOUGH IT'S EXPENSIVE, 
BECAUSE IF THE FIRST ONE FAILS

00:37:32.250 --> 00:37:33.999
THE SECOND ONE 
CAN TAKE ITS PLACE.

00:37:33.999 --> 00:37:35.999
IT SEEMS TO ME

00:37:35.999 --> 00:37:38.999
THAT ONCE YOU'VE GONE TO 
THE TROUBLE OF LAYING TWO EGGS

00:37:38.999 --> 00:37:39.999
AND YOU HAVE A GOOD SHOT

00:37:39.999 --> 00:37:42.959
AT HAVING TWO HEALTHY ADULTS 
COME OUT OF THAT

00:37:42.959 --> 00:37:46.999
ISN'T YOUR PURPOSE BETTER SERVED 
TO... TO LET BOTH OF THEM LIVE?

00:37:46.999 --> 00:37:48.999
YEAH, GOOD QUESTION.

00:37:48.999 --> 00:37:51.999
IF YOU EXPERIMENTALLY STOP 
THE SIBLICIDE FROM HAPPENING

00:37:51.999 --> 00:37:55.250
AND MAKE THEM PLAY NICE, 
AND THEN CHALLENGE THE PARENTS

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:56.999
TO BRING BACK 
ENOUGH FOOD FOR TWO

00:37:56.999 --> 00:37:58.999
ABOUT 30% OF THE TIME, 
THEY CAN DO IT.

00:37:58.999 --> 00:37:59.999
SHE DOESN'T STOP FEEDING.

00:37:59.999 --> 00:38:01.999
IF THERE ARE TWO CHICKS 
IN FRONT OF HER

00:38:01.999 --> 00:38:04.999
SHE'LL FEED THEM-- YOU KNOW, 
OPEN MOUTH, PUT IN FOOD--

00:38:04.999 --> 00:38:05.999
THAT'S WHAT SHE DOES.

00:38:05.999 --> 00:38:07.542
AND IF THERE ARE 
TWO OF THEM THERE

00:38:07.542 --> 00:38:08.999
SHE PUTS IT IN 
AT TWICE THE RATE.

00:38:08.999 --> 00:38:11.542
SO YOU SAY, "WELL, THEY 
DEFINITELY SHOULD BE STOPPING

00:38:11.542 --> 00:38:12.999
THE SIBLICIDE FROM HAPPENING."

00:38:12.999 --> 00:38:15.999
HOWEVER, IF YOU FOLLOW 
THOSE PARENTS ANOTHER YEAR

00:38:15.999 --> 00:38:19.000
YOU FIND OUT IN THE YEAR 
AFTER THEY RAISED TWO CHICKS

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:20.999
THEY TAKE IT ON THE CHIN 
IN TERMS OF SURVIVAL

00:38:20.999 --> 00:38:22.999
PARTICULARLY THE MOMS.

00:38:22.999 --> 00:38:26.834
REGULAR MOMS SURVIVE AT ABOUT 
92% OVER... FROM YEAR TO YEAR

00:38:26.834 --> 00:38:30.959
AND THE EXPERIMENTALS THAT 
HAVE HAD TO RAISE TWO CHICKS

00:38:30.959 --> 00:38:34.125
SURVIVE AT ABOUT 75%, 
AND THAT'S A HUGE COST.

00:38:34.125 --> 00:38:37.999
Alda: 
A COST THAT IN TERMS 
OF NATURAL SELECTION

00:38:37.999 --> 00:38:39.999
SIMPLY CANNOT BE SUSTAINED.

00:38:41.999 --> 00:38:44.999
Alda: 
THIS IS REALLY FASCINATING.

00:38:44.999 --> 00:38:46.834
BUT ON THE OTHER HAND

00:38:46.834 --> 00:38:49.999
I'M SPENDING JUST A FEW HOURS 
TALKING TO YOU ABOUT THIS

00:38:49.999 --> 00:38:52.834
AND YOU'RE SPENDING 
YOUR LIFE ON IT.

00:38:52.834 --> 00:38:54.667
HOW DID YOU GET LED TO THAT?

00:38:54.667 --> 00:38:55.999
IT'S A PROBLEM

00:38:55.999 --> 00:38:59.542
THAT ON THE SURFACE SEEMS 
FAIRLY EASY TO ADDRESS--

00:38:59.542 --> 00:39:02.125
THE PROBLEM BEING, 
WHY LAY THAT SECOND EGG?

00:39:02.125 --> 00:39:05.999
GIVEN THAT YOU LAY A SECOND EGG, 
WHY NOT TRY TO RAISE TWO CHICKS?

00:39:05.999 --> 00:39:09.834
BUT TO ACTUALLY LOOK AT HOW 
SELECTION ACTS ON INDIVIDUALS

00:39:09.834 --> 00:39:12.999
YOU REALLY OUGHT TO HAVE 
A LONG-TERM PERSPECTIVE

00:39:12.999 --> 00:39:14.999
AND FOLLOWING 
THE LIFETIME CONSEQUENCES

00:39:14.999 --> 00:39:17.999
OF A LONG-LIVED ANIMAL MAY 
TAKE UP MOST OF YOUR CAREER.

00:39:17.999 --> 00:39:22.999
SOME OF THE BIRDS THAT I HAVE 
INITIATED STUDY OF AS BABIES

00:39:22.999 --> 00:39:24.125
ARE GOING TO OUTLIVE MY CAREER.

00:39:25.999 --> 00:39:26.999
Alda: 
BUT MANY WON'T.

00:39:26.999 --> 00:39:29.999
EVEN CHICKS THAT HAVE WON 
THE BATTLE OF THE NEST

00:39:29.999 --> 00:39:32.999
FALL PREY TO MOCKINGBIRDS 
PECKING THEM FOR THEIR BLOOD.

00:39:36.999 --> 00:39:37.999
AND THEN THERE ARE

00:39:37.999 --> 00:39:40.999
THE CONSTANTLY MARAUDING 
FRIGATE BIRDS

00:39:40.999 --> 00:39:43.999
ALWAYS LOOKING TO SNATCH 
A CHICK FROM ITS NEST.

00:39:43.999 --> 00:39:46.999
Anderson: 
I MEAN, YOU EITHER GET 
KILLED BY YOUR SIBLING

00:39:46.999 --> 00:39:49.999
AND YOUR PARENTS DON'T CARE

00:39:49.999 --> 00:39:51.999
OR IF YOU MANAGE TO SURVIVE 
THAT PROCESS

00:39:51.999 --> 00:39:53.834
THEN WHEN YOUR PARENTS 
LEAVE YOU ALONE

00:39:53.834 --> 00:39:56.000
A FRIGATE BIRD MIGHT 
COME DOWN AND TAKE YOU

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:58.417
AND DROP YOU FROM 
A HUNDRED FEET IN THE AIR.

00:39:58.417 --> 00:40:01.999
Alda: 
DAVE ANDERSON'S LIFE AMONG 
THE MASKED BOOBIES OF ESPAÑOLA

00:40:01.999 --> 00:40:03.999
HAS GIVEN HIM UNUSUAL ACCESS

00:40:03.999 --> 00:40:05.999
TO THE DAILY STRUGGLE 
THAT DRIVES EVOLUTION.

00:40:05.999 --> 00:40:08.999
AND IT ISN'T A PRETTY SIGHT.

00:40:08.999 --> 00:40:12.999
LIFE STINKS FOR MOST ORGANISMS 
MOST OF THE TIME

00:40:12.999 --> 00:40:14.999
AND WE MAYBE DON'T 
REALIZE IT SO MUCH

00:40:14.999 --> 00:40:17.999
LOOKING AT CONTINENTAL SYSTEMS 
AS OPPOSED TO HERE

00:40:17.999 --> 00:40:20.999
BECAUSE HERE THE ANIMALS DO 
THEIR SUFFERING OUT IN THE OPEN

00:40:20.999 --> 00:40:23.999
AND PARTICULARLY 
THESE BOOBIES.

00:40:23.999 --> 00:40:25.250
THEY JUST HAVE A MISERABLE LIFE

00:40:25.250 --> 00:40:27.250
YOU WOULDN'T WISH 
ON YOUR WORST ENEMY--

00:40:27.250 --> 00:40:29.999
ALL THESE TERRIBLE THINGS 
THAT CAN HAPPEN TO YOU.

00:40:29.999 --> 00:40:33.417
AND IT'S REALLY APPARENT TO US, 
BECAUSE IT'S...

00:40:33.417 --> 00:40:34.999
THEY'RE NOT HIDING IT.

00:40:34.999 --> 00:40:35.999
THEY DON'T HAVE A HISTORY

00:40:35.999 --> 00:40:37.999
OF TRYING TO HIDE 
FROM CREATURES LIKE US

00:40:37.999 --> 00:40:39.999
AND SO THEY JUST DO IT 
IN FRONT OF US.

00:40:39.999 --> 00:40:43.999
WE CAN SORT OF PARTICIPATE 
IN THE COMMUNITY

00:40:43.999 --> 00:40:46.250
AS A KIND OF IGNORED OBSERVER

00:40:46.250 --> 00:40:49.999
WALKING DOWN THE BACK ALLEYS 
OF THEIR LIVES

00:40:49.999 --> 00:40:52.125
AND THEY SORT OF LET US DO IT.

00:41:07.999 --> 00:41:12.250
Alda: 
AMONG THE MORE RECENT IMMIGRANTS 
TO THE GALAPAGOS ARE HUMANS.

00:41:12.250 --> 00:41:14.999
WHEN DARWIN CAME IN 1835

00:41:14.999 --> 00:41:18.999
PEOPLE LIVED SCATTERED IN SMALL 
FISHING AND FARMING COMMUNITIES

00:41:18.999 --> 00:41:20.667
THROUGHOUT THE ARCHIPELAGO.

00:41:20.667 --> 00:41:22.250
WITH PEOPLE CAME ANIMALS

00:41:22.250 --> 00:41:24.999
THAT WOULD NEVER HAVE 
MADE IT HERE ON THEIR OWN:

00:41:24.999 --> 00:41:26.999
CHICKENS, DOGS, CATS..

00:41:26.999 --> 00:41:29.999
GOATS, PIGS, CATTLE.

00:41:30.999 --> 00:41:32.999
TODAY THERE ARE STRICT RULES

00:41:32.999 --> 00:41:36.999
GOVERNING WHERE PEOPLE 
AND THEIR ANIMALS CAN LIVE.

00:41:36.999 --> 00:41:39.999
96% OF THE LAND IS NATIONAL PARK

00:41:39.999 --> 00:41:42.999
OFF-LIMITS TO ANYONE 
NOT ACCOMPANIED BY A GUIDE

00:41:42.999 --> 00:41:43.999
LIKE LYNN FOWLER.

00:41:43.999 --> 00:41:45.999
BUT WHILE PEOPLE 
CAN BE CONTROLLED

00:41:45.999 --> 00:41:49.959
THE ANIMALS THEY'VE 
BROUGHT WITH THEM CAN'T.

00:41:49.959 --> 00:41:52.000
WE'RE CLIMBING A PEAK 
OVERLOOKING SANTIAGO

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:55.999
ONE OF THE FOUR ISLANDS 
ON DARWIN'S ITINERARY.

00:41:55.999 --> 00:41:57.999
Fowler: 
WHEN DARWIN 
CAMPED THERE...

00:41:57.999 --> 00:41:59.999
THAT'S ALL SANTIAGO 
OVER THERE?

00:41:59.999 --> 00:42:01.999
YEAH-- THERE 
WERE SO MANY 
LAND IGUANAS ON IT

00:42:01.999 --> 00:42:03.999
THAT HE COULD 
HARDLY FIND A PLACE

00:42:03.999 --> 00:42:04.999
TO PITCH HIS TENT

00:42:04.999 --> 00:42:06.000
BECAUSE OF THE 
LAND IGUANA BURROWS.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:07.000
( chuckles )

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.999
BUT THEY'RE 
EXTINCT NOW.

00:42:09.999 --> 00:42:11.999
THEY'RE EXTINCT 
FROM SANTIAGO.

00:42:11.999 --> 00:42:12.999
THOSE... REALLY?

00:42:12.999 --> 00:42:14.999
WELL, HOW DID 
THAT HAPPEN?

00:42:14.999 --> 00:42:16.999
DOGS AND PIGS... 
AND RATS.

00:42:16.999 --> 00:42:17.999
THEY GO 
RIGHT INTO THE...

00:42:17.999 --> 00:42:19.999
THE RATS ATTACK 
THE IGUANAS?

00:42:19.999 --> 00:42:21.250
THEY GO IN THE 
LAND IGUANA BURROWS

00:42:21.250 --> 00:42:23.999
AND EAT THE 
EGGS AND KILL THE 
LITTLE HATCHLINGS.

00:42:26.999 --> 00:42:29.999
Alda: 
ONE OF THE GALAPAGOS NATIVES 
WORST HIT BY HUMANS

00:42:29.999 --> 00:42:31.999
AND THE ANIMALS 
THEY BROUGHT WITH THEM

00:42:31.999 --> 00:42:33.999
IS THE GIANT TORTOISE.

00:42:33.999 --> 00:42:37.834
ORIGINALLY DECIMATED BY WHALERS 
HAULING THEM OFF FOR FOOD

00:42:37.834 --> 00:42:39.999
THEY HAVE SINCE HAD TO COMPETE 
WITH PIGS AND GOATS

00:42:39.999 --> 00:42:41.542
THAT HAVE GONE WILD 
AND RUN RAMPANT

00:42:41.542 --> 00:42:43.999
OVER MANY OF THE ISLANDS.

00:42:43.999 --> 00:42:45.667
( tortoise hissing )

00:42:48.999 --> 00:42:51.000
30 YEARS AGO, THE POPULATION

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:54.999
OF THE CHARACTERISTICALLY 
SADDLE-BACKED TORTOISES

00:42:54.999 --> 00:42:55.999
OF ESPAÑOLA

00:42:55.999 --> 00:42:58.999
WAS DOWN TO JUST 13-- 
12 FEMALES AND A MALE.

00:43:00.999 --> 00:43:03.999
BROUGHT HERE TO THE CHARLES 
DARWIN RESEARCH STATION

00:43:03.999 --> 00:43:07.417
ON THE ISLAND OF SANTA CRUZ, 
THESE 13 TORTOISES--

00:43:07.417 --> 00:43:10.999
AIDED BY A SECOND MALE RECRUITED 
FROM THE SAN DIEGO ZOO--

00:43:10.999 --> 00:43:13.999
HAVE SINCE PRODUCED 
HUNDREDS OF OFFSPRING.

00:43:14.999 --> 00:43:17.999
LAVISHLY FED AND 
KEPT SAFE FROM RATS

00:43:17.999 --> 00:43:20.999
UNTIL THEIR SHELLS ARE STRONG 
ENOUGH TO PROTECT THEM

00:43:20.999 --> 00:43:24.999
THE YOUNGSTERS HERE CAN 
LOOK FORWARD TO A LONG LIFE.

00:43:24.999 --> 00:43:25.999
LET ME JUST 
CURVE HIM IN.

00:43:25.999 --> 00:43:26.999
HERE WE GO.

00:43:28.999 --> 00:43:31.999
( laughing )

00:43:31.999 --> 00:43:32.999
DON'T BE SHY.

00:43:32.999 --> 00:43:33.999
HE'S HOW OLD?

00:43:33.999 --> 00:43:36.999
THIS ONE'S ABOUT 
A YEAR AND A HALF OLD.

00:43:36.999 --> 00:43:38.667
AND HOW OLD WILL 
HE GET TO BE

00:43:38.667 --> 00:43:39.999
IF HE'S LUCKY?

00:43:39.999 --> 00:43:40.999
WELL, WE CAN GUARANTEE

00:43:40.999 --> 00:43:43.999
THAT THEY LIVE BETWEEN 
60 AND 90 YEARS OLD

00:43:43.999 --> 00:43:46.999
BUT HISTORY BOOKS 
AND STORIES THAT ARE

00:43:46.999 --> 00:43:49.999
A BIT DIFFICULT TO CONFIRM SAY 
ANYTHING UP TO 150, 200 YEARS.

00:43:52.125 --> 00:43:54.667
Alda: 
THE PROJECT OWES ITS SUCCESS

00:43:54.667 --> 00:43:56.999
LARGELY TO THIS MAN, 
CRUZ MARQUEZ

00:43:56.999 --> 00:43:58.999
WHO WITH HIS COLLEAGUES 
HAS HAD TO INVENT

00:43:58.999 --> 00:44:02.250
THE CAPTIVE-BREEDING PROCESS 
AS THEY WENT ALONG.

00:44:02.250 --> 00:44:05.999
A CRITICAL REALIZATION WAS 
THAT THE SEX OF THE HATCHLINGS

00:44:05.999 --> 00:44:09.999
DEPENDS UPON THE TEMPERATURE AT 
WHICH THE EGGS ARE INCUBATED...

00:44:09.999 --> 00:44:11.999
ONE'S COMING 
OUT, HUH?

00:44:11.999 --> 00:44:14.999
Alda: 
29.5 DEGREES CELSIUS 
GIVES YOU FEMALES;

00:44:14.999 --> 00:44:18.999
28 DEGREES CELSIUS, 
AND YOU GET MALES.

00:44:18.999 --> 00:44:20.999
SOUNDS LIKE YOU 
MUST HAVE TO HAVE

00:44:20.999 --> 00:44:23.000
A PRETTY SOPHISTICATED 
SYSTEM HERE

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.999
TO KEEP THE TEMPERATURE 
WHAT YOU NEED IT TO BE.

00:44:25.999 --> 00:44:28.999
WE HAVE AN INCREDIBLY 
SOPHISTICATED SYSTEM.

00:44:28.999 --> 00:44:30.250
WE HAVE A HAIRDRYER

00:44:30.250 --> 00:44:34.834
CONNECTED TO A THERMOSTAT 
HERE, ON CONTINUOUS CYCLE.

00:44:34.834 --> 00:44:36.999
Alda: 
DESPITE THE SHOESTRING BUDGET

00:44:36.999 --> 00:44:39.999
THE CAPTIVE-BREEDING PROGRAM 
HAS RESULTED

00:44:39.999 --> 00:44:42.999
IN SOME 800 ESPAÑOLA TORTOISES 
BEING RETURNED

00:44:42.999 --> 00:44:44.999
TO THEIR NATIVE ISLAND.

00:44:44.999 --> 00:44:49.999
MAKING THIS POSSIBLE WAS AN 
AMBITIOUS AND SUCCESSFUL PROGRAM

00:44:49.999 --> 00:44:51.999
AIMED AT RIDDING 
THE ISLAND OF GOATS

00:44:51.999 --> 00:44:55.834
THE TORTOISES' MAIN 
COMPETITOR FOR RESOURCES.

00:44:56.999 --> 00:45:00.667
BUT MANY OF THE ISLANDS, 
INCLUDING THE BIGGEST, ISABELA

00:45:00.667 --> 00:45:02.999
REMAIN OVERRUN WITH GOATS 
AS WELL AS PIGS.

00:45:02.999 --> 00:45:05.125
THEIR ERADICATION IS 
A PRINCIPAL GOAL

00:45:05.125 --> 00:45:06.999
OF PEOPLE TRYING TO PRESERVE

00:45:06.999 --> 00:45:09.999
THE ISLANDS' UNIQUE 
BIOLOGICAL HERITAGE--

00:45:09.999 --> 00:45:13.999
PEOPLE LIKE THE DARWIN RESEARCH 
STATION'S HOWARD SNELL.

00:45:13.999 --> 00:45:17.999
WE'RE COMING INTO ELIZABETH BAY 
OFF THE COAST OF ISABELA

00:45:17.999 --> 00:45:19.999
THE LARGEST ISLAND 
IN THE GALAPAGOS

00:45:19.999 --> 00:45:22.417
AND THESE ARE 
THE MARIELAS ISLETS.

00:45:22.417 --> 00:45:24.999
Alda: 
BUT FOR SOME INTRODUCED SPECIES

00:45:24.999 --> 00:45:26.999
ERADICATION IS 
ALL BUT IMPOSSIBLE.

00:45:28.542 --> 00:45:30.999
RATS, FOR INSTANCE, 
HAVE BEEN IN THE GALAPAGOS

00:45:30.999 --> 00:45:32.999
AS LONG AS SHIPS 
HAVE VISITED HERE.

00:45:32.999 --> 00:45:35.999
THEY APPEAR TO HAVE INVADED THE 
MARIELAS ISLANDS ONLY RECENTLY

00:45:35.999 --> 00:45:37.834
BUT NOW MAY BE THREATENING

00:45:37.834 --> 00:45:39.999
ONE OF THE GALAPAGOS'S 
MOST UNEXPECTED INHABITANTS.

00:45:39.999 --> 00:45:41.999
Snell: 
PENGUINS IN 
THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS

00:45:41.999 --> 00:45:43.999
ARE THE NORTHERNMOST PENGUINS 
IN THE WORLD.

00:45:43.999 --> 00:45:45.999
SO IT'S A UNIQUE 
KIND OF PENGUIN.

00:45:45.999 --> 00:45:47.999
BUT UNFORTUNATELY, 
THE PENGUINS IN GALAPAGOS

00:45:47.999 --> 00:45:49.999
AREN'T DOING PARTICULARLY WELL.

00:45:49.999 --> 00:45:52.542
WHEN EL NIÑO EVENTS COME 
INTO THE ARCHIPELAGO

00:45:52.542 --> 00:45:55.999
WHICH HAPPENS EVERY SO OFTEN, 
THE WATERS GET VERY, VERY WARM

00:45:55.999 --> 00:45:58.999
AND THE NORMAL FISH LIFE 
AROUND HERE BEGINS TO DIE OFF.

00:45:58.999 --> 00:46:01.542
WHEN THAT HAPPENS, 
PENGUIN POPULATIONS CRASH.

00:46:01.542 --> 00:46:03.999
IN 1982-'83, THEY 
CRASHED BY OVER 50%.

00:46:03.999 --> 00:46:06.959
THIS LAST YEAR, '97-'98, 
THEY CRASHED AGAIN.

00:46:06.959 --> 00:46:08.542
AND THE THING THAT CONFUSES US

00:46:08.542 --> 00:46:10.999
IS THEY DON'T RECUPERATE 
AFTER THOSE CRASHES.

00:46:10.999 --> 00:46:13.667
NOW, THAT WORRIES US, 
BECAUSE, OF COURSE

00:46:13.667 --> 00:46:16.999
IF THE POPULATIONS CRASH EVERY 
SO OFTEN AND NEVER RECUPERATE

00:46:16.999 --> 00:46:18.999
THEY CAN GO EXTINCT.

00:46:18.999 --> 00:46:20.999
Alda: 
HOWARD SUSPECTS RATS 
ARE THE CULPRITS

00:46:20.999 --> 00:46:22.999
INVADING THE ROCK CREVICES

00:46:22.999 --> 00:46:25.999
WHERE PENGUINS LAY THEIR EGGS 
AND RAISE THEIR CHICKS.

00:46:25.999 --> 00:46:27.999
SO HE'S CONDUCTING AN EXPERIMENT

00:46:27.999 --> 00:46:30.999
TO SEE WHAT CAN BE DONE 
TO SAVE THE PENGUINS--

00:46:30.999 --> 00:46:32.542
SHORT OF THE IMPOSSIBLE TASK

00:46:32.542 --> 00:46:35.250
OF RIDDING THE GALAPAGOS 
OF RATS ENTIRELY.

00:46:35.250 --> 00:46:38.000
Snell: 
NOW, WHAT WE'RE TRYING TO DO 
IS USE THESE ISLANDS--

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:41.999
THESE SMALL ISLANDS-- AS MODELS 
FOR THE REST OF THE GALAPAGOS.

00:46:41.999 --> 00:46:44.667
AND WE'RE REMOVING THE RATS, 
BY POISONING THEM

00:46:44.667 --> 00:46:47.834
FROM SOME OF THE ISLANDS 
AND LEAVING THEM ON OTHERS.

00:46:48.999 --> 00:46:52.999
THE IDEA IS TO TRY AND MEASURE 
HOW FEW RATS WE CAN REMOVE

00:46:52.999 --> 00:46:54.999
TO INCREASE 
PENGUIN REPRODUCTION.

00:46:54.999 --> 00:46:56.999
THAT WAY WE CAN 
INVEST ENOUGH MONEY

00:46:56.999 --> 00:46:58.999
TO INCREASE PENGUIN REPRODUCTION

00:46:58.999 --> 00:47:02.125
BUT NOT SO MUCH MONEY THAT 
WE CAN'T DO OTHER THINGS ALSO.

00:47:02.125 --> 00:47:04.999
IT'S REALLY ABOUT TRYING 
TO DIVVY UP LIMITED RESOURCES

00:47:04.999 --> 00:47:05.999
FOR THE CONSERVATION

00:47:05.999 --> 00:47:07.999
OF THE BIOLOGY 
OF THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS.

00:47:07.999 --> 00:47:11.999
Alda: 
THOSE RESOURCES MAY BECOME 
A LITTLE LESS LIMITED

00:47:11.999 --> 00:47:15.000
IN THE FUTURE, THANKS 
TO THE LATEST ALIEN SPECIES

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.667
TO INVADE THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS:

00:47:17.667 --> 00:47:20.999
ECO-TOURISTS, WHO COME 
BY THE THOUSANDS EACH YEAR.

00:47:20.999 --> 00:47:23.999
THESE TOURISTS BRING IN 
MILLIONS OF DOLLARS

00:47:23.999 --> 00:47:25.999
FOR THE TOUR OPERATORS

00:47:25.999 --> 00:47:29.999
BUT UNTIL RECENTLY, LITTLE 
OR NOTHING FOR THE WILDLIFE.

00:47:29.999 --> 00:47:31.834
NOW THAT'S CHANGING.

00:47:31.834 --> 00:47:34.999
Man: 
THERE ARE ABOUT 60,000 PEOPLE 
A YEAR WHO VISIT THE GALAPAGOS

00:47:34.999 --> 00:47:37.999
AND I'M OF THE BELIEF 
THAT THOSE 60,000 PEOPLE

00:47:37.999 --> 00:47:40.999
CAN BE A MAJOR PART 
OF THE FUTURE IN THESE ISLANDS

00:47:40.999 --> 00:47:42.999
AND THAT COMPANIES 
LIKE OURSELVES

00:47:42.999 --> 00:47:44.667
WHO BENEFIT AND INDEED PROFIT

00:47:44.667 --> 00:47:46.999
FROM BEING ABLE TO BRING 
THESE VISITORS HERE

00:47:46.999 --> 00:47:49.417
ARE IN THE POSITION 
TO MAKE A DIFFERENCE.

00:47:49.417 --> 00:47:52.959
AND IN THE LAST YEAR, 
IN THE YEAR SINCE 
WE'VE BEEN HERE

00:47:52.959 --> 00:47:54.999
WE'VE RAISED ABOUT 
$200,000 FROM OUR GUESTS

00:47:54.999 --> 00:47:56.999
AND WHEN YOU THINK 
THAT WE REPRESENT

00:47:56.999 --> 00:47:59.999
FIVE PERCENT OF TOURISM 
TO THESE ISLANDS

00:47:59.999 --> 00:48:02.999
AND IF YOU MULTIPLY THIS KIND 
OF AN ACTIVITY TIMES 20

00:48:02.999 --> 00:48:06.667
ALL OF A SUDDEN, TOURISM COULD, 
IN FACT, SUSTAIN PLACES

00:48:06.667 --> 00:48:10.999
LIKE THE CHARLES DARWIN RESEARCH 
STATION AND THE NATIONAL PARKS

00:48:10.999 --> 00:48:13.999
AND THEY WOULDN'T HAVE 
TO STRUGGLE SO MUCH FOR FUNDING.

00:48:15.999 --> 00:48:17.999
Alda: 
BUT THERE'S AN IRONY HERE.

00:48:17.999 --> 00:48:19.999
TOURISTS BRING IN 
NOT ONLY DOLLARS;

00:48:19.999 --> 00:48:22.999
THEY'VE ALSO ATTRACTED THOUSANDS 
OF ECUADORIANS TO THE ISLANDS

00:48:22.999 --> 00:48:24.999
TO WORK IN THE TOURISM INDUSTRY.

00:48:27.999 --> 00:48:30.999
TOGETHER, TOURISTS AND 
RESIDENTS POSE A NEW THREAT

00:48:30.999 --> 00:48:31.999
TO THE ISLANDS' ECOSYSTEM.

00:48:31.999 --> 00:48:34.999
Snell: 
BECAUSE THERE ARE 16,000 
TO 20,000 PEOPLE

00:48:34.999 --> 00:48:36.999
THAT LIVE IN 
THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS

00:48:36.999 --> 00:48:39.999
FIVE SUPPLY SHIPS RUN OUT HERE 
TWO OR THREE TIMES A MONTH EACH

00:48:39.999 --> 00:48:41.999
AND THERE ARE THREE 727s A DAY

00:48:41.999 --> 00:48:43.999
THAT FLY INTO 
THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS.

00:48:43.999 --> 00:48:47.999
ALL OF THAT ACTIVITY BRINGS IN 
A TREMENDOUS AMOUNT OF MATERIAL.

00:48:47.999 --> 00:48:50.999
TONS AND TONS AND TONS OF FOOD 
AND CONSTRUCTION MATERIAL

00:48:50.999 --> 00:48:52.999
COME TO THE GALAPAGOS 
EVERY YEAR.

00:48:52.999 --> 00:48:53.999
SOMEWHERE IN THOSE PACKAGES

00:48:53.999 --> 00:48:55.999
ARE THE INTRODUCED SPECIES 
OF TOMORROW.

00:48:55.999 --> 00:48:57.999
IT'S NOT PURPOSEFUL NOWADAYS

00:48:57.999 --> 00:49:00.999
BUT IT'S EVERY BIT 
AS DAMAGING AS IF IT WAS.

00:49:00.999 --> 00:49:02.999
Alda: 
I'VE COME TO SEE FOR MYSELF

00:49:02.999 --> 00:49:05.999
ONE OF THE WORST 
OF THESE ALIEN INVADERS.

00:49:05.999 --> 00:49:08.999
CHARLOTTE CAUSTON 
OF THE DARWIN RESEARCH STATION

00:49:08.999 --> 00:49:09.999
IS SHOWING THE WAY.

00:49:09.999 --> 00:49:12.999
WHAT ARE ALL THESE 
LITTLE WHITE THINGS?

00:49:12.999 --> 00:49:15.999
OKAY, THESE 
ARE THE COTTONY 
CUSHION SCALE.

00:49:15.999 --> 00:49:18.667
IT'S AN INTRODUCED 
SCALE INSECT

00:49:18.667 --> 00:49:20.542
THAT WAS INTRODUCED 
IN 1982

00:49:20.542 --> 00:49:22.999
INTO THE ISLAND 
OF SAN CRISTOBAL

00:49:22.999 --> 00:49:24.999
AND HAS SINCE 
THEN SPREAD

00:49:24.999 --> 00:49:27.999
TO NINE OTHER ISLANDS 
IN THE ARCHIPELAGO

00:49:27.999 --> 00:49:29.999
AND ATTACKS OVER 
40 PLANT SPECIES.

00:49:29.999 --> 00:49:31.250
HMM...

00:49:31.250 --> 00:49:33.999
IN THE ABSENCE OF 
ITS NATURAL ENEMIES

00:49:33.999 --> 00:49:34.999
IT'S JUST GONE HAYWIRE.

00:49:34.999 --> 00:49:36.999
HOW WAS IT INTRODUCED?

00:49:36.999 --> 00:49:38.999
WE'RE NOT SURE.

00:49:38.999 --> 00:49:40.000
WE THINK IT WAS INTRODUCED

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:43.542
IN SOME ACACIA TREES THAT 
WERE IMPORTED TO THE ISLANDS

00:49:43.542 --> 00:49:45.959
BUT THEN AGAIN, IT COULD 
HAVE BEEN SOME CITRUS.

00:49:45.959 --> 00:49:48.250
AND IT WAS DEFINITELY ON A PLANT 
AND ACCIDENTALLY INTRODUCED.

00:49:48.250 --> 00:49:49.999
NO ONE BROUGHT IT IN ON PURPOSE.

00:49:49.999 --> 00:49:54.999
Alda: 
THE COTTONY CUSHION SCALE IS ONE 
OF HUNDREDS OF NONNATIVE INSECTS

00:49:54.999 --> 00:49:57.125
THAT HAVE RECENTLY SNEAKED 
INTO THE ISLANDS

00:49:57.125 --> 00:50:00.417
AND CHARLOTTE IS ONE 
OF ONLY TWO ENTOMOLOGISTS.

00:50:00.417 --> 00:50:02.999
IF YOU HAVE TO GO AFTER THEM 
SPECIES BY SPECIES

00:50:02.999 --> 00:50:04.999
FIND OUT WHAT THEY DO, 
WHAT HARM THEY CAUSE

00:50:04.999 --> 00:50:07.542
AND THEN HOW YOU CAN 
PROTECT AGAINST THEM--

00:50:07.542 --> 00:50:09.999
AND BY THE TIME YOU FIND 
THAT OUT ABOUT ONE SPECIES

00:50:09.999 --> 00:50:12.999
YOU'VE PROBABLY GOT 
ANOTHER 300 ON YOUR LIST.

00:50:12.999 --> 00:50:13.999
THAT'S RIGHT.

00:50:13.999 --> 00:50:15.000
HOW DOES THAT 
MAKE YOU FEEL?

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:17.125
IT'S DAUNTING, THE PROSPECT.

00:50:17.125 --> 00:50:20.999
THE MAGNITUDE OF THE PROBLEMS 
THAT FACE THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS

00:50:20.999 --> 00:50:23.999
CAN APPEAR OVERWHELMING, AND 
IN FACT, THEY ARE OVERWHELMING

00:50:23.999 --> 00:50:26.999
BUT THE ONE THING THAT 
PEOPLE THAT ARE MOTIVATED

00:50:26.999 --> 00:50:29.999
TO CONSERVE BIOLOGICAL DIVERSITY 
IN THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS

00:50:29.999 --> 00:50:33.125
KEEP AT THE FOREFRONT ALL OF 
THE TIME IS THAT THIS IS REALLY

00:50:33.125 --> 00:50:35.999
ONE OF THE LAST OCEANIC 
ARCHIPELAGOS IN THE WORLD

00:50:35.999 --> 00:50:39.999
WHERE WE HAVE AN OPPORTUNITY TO 
MAINTAIN A PRISTINE ENVIRONMENT.

00:50:39.999 --> 00:50:42.999
THERE ARE... 95% TO 96% OF 
THE SPECIES THAT EVER OCCURRED

00:50:42.999 --> 00:50:45.000
IN THE GALAPAGOS ISLANDS 
ARE ALIVE TODAY.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:46.999
SOME OF THEM ARE IN A BAD STATE.

00:50:46.999 --> 00:50:48.999
SOME OF THEM MAY GO EXTINCT 
BEFORE TOO LONG

00:50:48.999 --> 00:50:51.000
IF WE'RE NOT SUCCESSFUL 
AT RESTORATION EFFORTS FOR THEM.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:53.417
